1
00:03:40,178 --> 00:03:41,668
Ms. Roberts,

2
00:03:41,680 --> 00:03:44,342
is it true that while we are
here at this news conference,

3
00:03:44,349 --> 00:03:46,260
the Indians are honoring
the students who were killed,

4
00:03:46,268 --> 00:03:49,226
in a special burial ceremony
out on the reservation?

5
00:03:49,229 --> 00:03:50,435
Ms. Roberts,

6
00:03:50,439 --> 00:03:51,725
has it ever happened before

7
00:03:51,732 --> 00:03:53,939
that so many thousands
of rounds of ammunition

8
00:03:53,942 --> 00:03:55,228
were fired
into the dormitories

9
00:03:55,235 --> 00:03:57,522
in such a short period
of time?

10
00:03:57,529 --> 00:04:00,521
It happened many times
before here.

11
00:04:00,532 --> 00:04:04,116
Kent State,
the Orangeburg Massacre--

12
00:04:04,119 --> 00:04:07,453
27 kids were shot
at that one.

13
00:04:07,456 --> 00:04:09,948
Or Jackson State
or Houston,

14
00:04:09,958 --> 00:04:13,167
any one
of a dozen others.

15
00:04:13,170 --> 00:04:15,457
Students are slaughtered
by trigger happy police,

16
00:04:15,464 --> 00:04:17,546
and nothing
is ever done about it.

17
00:04:17,549 --> 00:04:20,587
Besides Billy Jack,
who else was shot?

18
00:04:20,594 --> 00:04:22,301
How many
were actually killed?

19
00:04:26,183 --> 00:04:29,551
There were three deaths,

20
00:04:29,561 --> 00:04:31,928
and two still
on the critical list.

21
00:05:44,970 --> 00:05:46,802
<i>Dr. Bernard Russert,</i>

22
00:05:46,805 --> 00:05:48,011
<i>Dr. Russert.</i>

23
00:05:48,014 --> 00:05:49,470
Has Washington replied

24
00:05:49,474 --> 00:05:52,762
to your request
for an investigation?

25
00:05:52,769 --> 00:05:54,976
Are you kidding?

26
00:05:54,980 --> 00:05:56,937
Remember after Kent State

27
00:05:56,940 --> 00:05:58,806
how Attorney General
John Mitchell said

28
00:05:58,817 --> 00:06:02,481
there was no need to explore
the causes of the killings

29
00:06:02,487 --> 00:06:03,977
because he knew in advance

30
00:06:03,989 --> 00:06:05,400
the causes
couldn't possibly be

31
00:06:05,407 --> 00:06:07,739
the National Guard
or the police.

32
00:06:07,742 --> 00:06:10,074
But didn't an FBI
report subsequently prove

33
00:06:10,078 --> 00:06:12,490
that there were no shots fired
by the students

34
00:06:12,497 --> 00:06:16,035
but there was grave culpability
on the part of the Guard?

35
00:06:16,042 --> 00:06:17,999
They sure did.

36
00:06:18,003 --> 00:06:20,665
But, as usual, Washington
did nothing about it.

37
00:06:20,672 --> 00:06:23,414
Does this mean that it's
the end of the school?

38
00:06:23,425 --> 00:06:28,340
Will you have to close
it down now?

39
00:06:28,346 --> 00:06:31,259
Maybe.

40
00:06:31,266 --> 00:06:32,552
Maybe not.

41
00:06:34,352 --> 00:06:36,263
I honestly don't know
at this point.

42
00:06:38,189 --> 00:06:40,681
I'm sorry, folks,
Ms. Roberts is very tired.

43
00:06:40,692 --> 00:06:42,603
You're going to have to leave.

44
00:06:44,321 --> 00:06:45,811
Thank you, Ms. Roberts.

45
00:06:52,203 --> 00:06:54,194
My publisher still
thinks that it's vital

46
00:06:54,205 --> 00:06:56,537
that a book be done
about your school

47
00:06:56,541 --> 00:06:58,373
and how the massacre
happened there.

48
00:07:00,378 --> 00:07:02,494
I wouldn't even know
where to begin.

49
00:07:02,505 --> 00:07:04,746
Maybe you could start with
the arrest of Billy Jack.

50
00:07:07,510 --> 00:07:09,467
Wasn't it what happened
at the trial

51
00:07:09,471 --> 00:07:12,008
that made you so determined
to make the school succeed?

52
00:07:14,851 --> 00:07:17,058
Yes.

53
00:07:17,062 --> 00:07:20,726
That was-- what--

54
00:07:20,732 --> 00:07:23,099
four, four and half years ago.

55
00:07:25,528 --> 00:07:28,065
Wasn't Billy Jack's
main belief

56
00:07:28,073 --> 00:07:30,906
that a man who doesn't go
his own way is nothing?

57
00:07:33,411 --> 00:07:35,072
That's right.

58
00:07:35,080 --> 00:07:37,868
That's why they tried Billy.

59
00:07:37,874 --> 00:07:39,956
But we all knew that
what they were really trying

60
00:07:39,960 --> 00:07:44,079
was each man's right
to find his own center,

61
00:07:44,089 --> 00:07:45,579
to follow his own conscience

62
00:07:45,590 --> 00:07:48,048
and to do his own thing

63
00:07:48,051 --> 00:07:51,965
without hurting or interfering
with anybody else's.

64
00:07:54,599 --> 00:07:58,558
<i>That ideal, to all of us,
was Billy Jack.</i>

65
00:07:58,561 --> 00:08:00,268
What your saying, then,

66
00:08:00,271 --> 00:08:02,387
is that it doesn't make
any difference to you

67
00:08:02,399 --> 00:08:07,314
whether this jury finds you
innocent or guilty,

68
00:08:07,320 --> 00:08:09,778
and it doesn't make
any difference to you

69
00:08:09,781 --> 00:08:11,647
whether you live or die.

70
00:08:13,284 --> 00:08:15,321
You expect us to believe

71
00:08:15,328 --> 00:08:18,446
that you have absolutely
no fear of the death penalty?

72
00:08:21,876 --> 00:08:24,459
I have a lot of fear,

73
00:08:24,462 --> 00:08:26,920
but I have a lot more respect.

74
00:08:26,923 --> 00:08:30,632
Long ago I learned that he
is my constant companion.

75
00:08:30,635 --> 00:08:32,501
He eats with me,
he walks with me,

76
00:08:32,512 --> 00:08:34,469
he even sleeps with me.

77
00:08:34,472 --> 00:08:38,511
I'm sorry, I must have
missed something back there.

78
00:08:38,518 --> 00:08:41,135
Who is this faithful
companion of yours?

79
00:08:42,272 --> 00:08:46,436
- Death.
- Oh, I see.

80
00:08:46,443 --> 00:08:50,152
Tell me, is this death
companion business

81
00:08:50,155 --> 00:08:53,238
some special part
of your Indian beliefs?

82
00:08:53,241 --> 00:08:54,652
No.

83
00:08:54,659 --> 00:08:57,742
Every one of us has death
as his constant companion.

84
00:08:57,746 --> 00:09:00,534
He sits with every one of us
every second of our lives,

85
00:09:00,540 --> 00:09:03,498
only we're too terrified
to really think about that,

86
00:09:03,501 --> 00:09:05,162
but once you do,

87
00:09:05,170 --> 00:09:07,832
it will completely change
your entire outlook on life.

88
00:09:07,839 --> 00:09:10,501
How so?

89
00:09:10,508 --> 00:09:11,998
You ask yourself,

90
00:09:12,010 --> 00:09:14,377
even in
the most serious crisis,

91
00:09:14,387 --> 00:09:16,094
how important
would this really be

92
00:09:16,097 --> 00:09:17,337
if I were suddenly told

93
00:09:17,348 --> 00:09:20,010
that I just had
one more week to live?

94
00:09:20,018 --> 00:09:23,101
So, you learn to take
nothing too seriously.

95
00:09:23,104 --> 00:09:24,765
On the other hand,

96
00:09:24,773 --> 00:09:26,184
you ask yourself,

97
00:09:26,191 --> 00:09:28,228
if this were
my last act on earth,

98
00:09:28,234 --> 00:09:31,147
is this what
I really want to do?

99
00:09:31,154 --> 00:09:32,736
So you learn on the one hand

100
00:09:32,739 --> 00:09:35,857
to be detached from the
temporary things of this world,

101
00:09:35,867 --> 00:09:38,154
and on the other hand
you learn to appreciate

102
00:09:38,161 --> 00:09:40,493
every little thing in it
all the more.

103
00:09:43,041 --> 00:09:45,533
<i>During the trial,
Sheriff Cole resigned,</i>

104
00:09:45,543 --> 00:09:47,250
<i>and Posner,</i>

105
00:09:47,253 --> 00:09:50,462
<i>who never really quite recovered
from the death of his son,</i>

106
00:09:50,465 --> 00:09:52,001
<i>sold out all of his companies</i>

107
00:09:52,008 --> 00:09:53,544
<i>to his brother the banker,</i>

108
00:09:53,551 --> 00:09:55,588
<i>and he quietly left town.</i>

109
00:09:55,595 --> 00:09:57,836
<i>And though we were happy
about it then,</i>

110
00:09:57,847 --> 00:09:59,838
<i>it turned out to be
one of the worst things</i>

111
00:09:59,849 --> 00:10:01,840
<i>that ever happened to us.</i>

112
00:10:01,851 --> 00:10:03,842
<i>The prosecution,
for it's part,</i>

113
00:10:03,853 --> 00:10:06,641
<i>savagely attacked
our character</i>

114
00:10:06,648 --> 00:10:09,731
<i>and tried to make it look
like I wasn't even raped.</i>

115
00:10:09,734 --> 00:10:12,601
So Miss Garrison lies,
and you swear to it.

116
00:10:12,612 --> 00:10:15,695
- Objection.
- Sustained.

117
00:10:15,698 --> 00:10:17,234
Now, Ms. Roberts,

118
00:10:17,242 --> 00:10:20,405
isn't it true
that you were never raped?

119
00:10:20,411 --> 00:10:21,572
Isn't it true

120
00:10:21,579 --> 00:10:23,115
that you made up this story

121
00:10:23,123 --> 00:10:24,659
in a desperate attempt

122
00:10:24,666 --> 00:10:26,327
to try and justify

123
00:10:26,334 --> 00:10:28,120
the violent
and insane killing

124
00:10:28,128 --> 00:10:29,414
by the man you love?

125
00:10:29,420 --> 00:10:30,706
Objection.

126
00:10:32,590 --> 00:10:34,080
Order.

127
00:10:34,092 --> 00:10:37,210
I feel terribly sorry for
your children, Mr. Williams.

128
00:10:37,220 --> 00:10:40,554
You feel sorry
for my children?

129
00:10:40,557 --> 00:10:42,298
Yes, and you, too.

130
00:10:42,308 --> 00:10:46,097
You know me,
and you know I don't lie.

131
00:10:46,104 --> 00:10:48,846
It must be terribly
degrading for you to pretend

132
00:10:48,857 --> 00:10:50,689
in front of all
of these people, that I do,

133
00:10:50,692 --> 00:10:52,103
just to earn your money.

134
00:10:56,281 --> 00:10:58,773
Yes, I was proud
to go through West Point.

135
00:10:58,783 --> 00:11:01,696
I was taught there
a code of honor and manliness

136
00:11:01,703 --> 00:11:03,614
that, while it went
overboard at times,

137
00:11:03,621 --> 00:11:05,203
I basically liked.

138
00:11:05,206 --> 00:11:07,789
Yet you brought charges
against your own officers,

139
00:11:07,792 --> 00:11:09,874
including two staff commanders
and a general.

140
00:11:09,878 --> 00:11:11,460
That's right.

141
00:11:11,462 --> 00:11:14,796
I charged them with the
deliberate and senseless

142
00:11:14,799 --> 00:11:17,086
slaughtering of innocent women
and children in the field

143
00:11:17,093 --> 00:11:20,336
either directly
or by men under their command,

144
00:11:20,346 --> 00:11:22,804
and by failing to report
these atrocities

145
00:11:22,807 --> 00:11:25,344
or covering them up
with full knowledge of same.

146
00:11:25,351 --> 00:11:27,342
And after you proffered
these charges,

147
00:11:27,353 --> 00:11:30,311
the Army suddenly made up
charges against you,

148
00:11:30,315 --> 00:11:32,556
of cowardice in the field,

149
00:11:32,567 --> 00:11:34,979
and they offered to drop
these charges against you

150
00:11:34,986 --> 00:11:37,318
if you would drop them
against the officers.

151
00:11:37,322 --> 00:11:38,653
That's correct.

152
00:11:38,656 --> 00:11:40,897
And did you refuse
to drop the charges?

153
00:11:40,909 --> 00:11:42,616
I did refuse

154
00:11:42,619 --> 00:11:44,405
Could you please tell us
in your own words

155
00:11:44,412 --> 00:11:47,245
exactly what led up to your
refusing to obey

156
00:11:47,248 --> 00:11:48,579
this order in the field?

157
00:11:48,583 --> 00:11:52,827
Was it before
or after My Lai?

158
00:11:52,837 --> 00:11:56,046
It was about seven months
before My Lai.

159
00:11:56,049 --> 00:11:58,837
We were out
on a search-and-destroy mission

160
00:11:58,843 --> 00:12:02,552
on a small
South Vietnamese hamlet.

161
00:12:02,555 --> 00:12:04,011
Just like at My Lai,

162
00:12:04,015 --> 00:12:05,722
there had been plenty
of advance warnings,

163
00:12:05,725 --> 00:12:08,183
so when we got there,
there was no resistance,

164
00:12:08,186 --> 00:12:10,223
no military in sight.

165
00:12:10,230 --> 00:12:12,517
Not a shot was fired.

166
00:12:12,523 --> 00:12:13,979
All the village
was filled with

167
00:12:13,983 --> 00:12:16,520
was women, children,
and old men.

168
00:12:16,527 --> 00:12:18,814
They were frightened
and very eager to please,

169
00:12:18,821 --> 00:12:22,314
so we quickly herded them up
into a ditch,

170
00:12:22,325 --> 00:12:24,657
and we sat around waiting
for several hours

171
00:12:24,661 --> 00:12:26,197
for some word
from headquarters

172
00:12:26,204 --> 00:12:28,366
as to what we were to do
with them.

173
00:12:28,373 --> 00:12:29,784
People in the meantime

174
00:12:29,791 --> 00:12:32,829
were kept in the ditch
in the boiling sun,

175
00:12:32,835 --> 00:12:34,576
and were not allowed
to relieve themselves

176
00:12:34,587 --> 00:12:36,578
or go for any water.

177
00:12:36,589 --> 00:12:38,045
Get them in the ditch!

178
00:12:38,049 --> 00:12:39,039
Way down to the end.

179
00:12:47,767 --> 00:12:49,678
There must be some mistake.

180
00:12:49,686 --> 00:12:51,723
There's no mistake, sir.

181
00:12:51,729 --> 00:12:53,561
The order was perfectly clear.

182
00:12:57,902 --> 00:12:59,688
Get me headquarters
on the phone again.

183
00:13:01,155 --> 00:13:02,987
Give me that phone.
I want to hear it myself.

184
00:13:06,077 --> 00:13:10,036
If you fellows refuse,
all hell can break loose.

185
00:13:10,039 --> 00:13:11,655
You know that.

186
00:13:14,919 --> 00:13:16,455
Are you absolutely sure, sir?

187
00:13:18,881 --> 00:13:20,463
There can be no mistake
down the line?

188
00:13:21,801 --> 00:13:24,042
Yes, sir.
I understand, sir.

189
00:13:31,269 --> 00:13:32,350
Waste them.

190
00:13:35,732 --> 00:13:37,018
You mean the civilians?

191
00:13:39,319 --> 00:13:41,310
That's the order,
clear as hell.

192
00:13:41,321 --> 00:13:43,779
Direct from Saigon.

193
00:13:43,781 --> 00:13:45,237
We're to waste them.

194
00:13:47,577 --> 00:13:50,069
All right,
all you men on your feet.

195
00:13:58,755 --> 00:14:00,211
Think clearly, now.

196
00:14:02,216 --> 00:14:04,958
You disobey this order,
and they can hang you.

197
00:14:04,969 --> 00:14:05,879
Lock and load!

198
00:14:14,812 --> 00:14:16,598
God almighty.

199
00:14:17,940 --> 00:14:19,726
What's happening to us?

200
00:14:19,734 --> 00:14:21,645
Aim!

201
00:14:28,534 --> 00:14:30,275
Fire!

202
00:15:02,110 --> 00:15:05,273
So it was this
senseless slaughter

203
00:15:05,279 --> 00:15:07,111
and sadistic brutality

204
00:15:07,115 --> 00:15:09,026
coming as official orders
from Washington

205
00:15:09,033 --> 00:15:11,274
that turned you
against America.

206
00:15:11,285 --> 00:15:13,117
No, not really.

207
00:15:13,121 --> 00:15:15,203
In war,
when you've brainwashed men

208
00:15:15,206 --> 00:15:16,822
to become
cold-blooded killers,

209
00:15:16,833 --> 00:15:19,120
you expect them to kill.

210
00:15:19,127 --> 00:15:21,869
Then what was it that made
you bitter toward America?

211
00:15:21,879 --> 00:15:25,167
- Lieutenant Calley.
- Lieutenant Calley?

212
00:15:25,174 --> 00:15:28,462
You mean because he was tried
for war crimes at My Lai?

213
00:15:28,469 --> 00:15:30,255
No, he should have been tried.

214
00:15:30,263 --> 00:15:32,846
And so should all those
Colonels and Generals

215
00:15:32,849 --> 00:15:34,260
and White-House Aids

216
00:15:34,267 --> 00:15:35,507
who ordered the whole affair

217
00:15:35,518 --> 00:15:38,431
but were mysteriously let off
soot-free.

218
00:15:38,438 --> 00:15:40,770
Then why Lieutenant Calley?

219
00:15:40,773 --> 00:15:43,606
Because America made him
into such a great hero.

220
00:15:43,609 --> 00:15:48,024
To me they were sick and
diseased men filled with evil,

221
00:15:48,030 --> 00:15:49,646
who cut
innocent women's throats

222
00:15:49,657 --> 00:15:51,523
and blew out the brains
of babies,

223
00:15:51,534 --> 00:15:54,151
and America had raised him up

224
00:15:54,162 --> 00:15:55,402
and made him an national idol.

225
00:15:56,914 --> 00:15:58,450
What was that part

226
00:15:58,458 --> 00:16:00,540
about the President
switching his colors?

227
00:16:00,543 --> 00:16:02,830
On December <i>8</i> 1969,

228
00:16:02,837 --> 00:16:04,874
every newspaper
in this country

229
00:16:04,881 --> 00:16:07,623
carried President Nixon's
sacred promise

230
00:16:07,633 --> 00:16:09,965
that he would personally
investigate My Lai

231
00:16:09,969 --> 00:16:11,551
and he would personally
see to it

232
00:16:11,554 --> 00:16:14,012
that everyone involved,
if they were found guilty,

233
00:16:14,015 --> 00:16:16,052
was punished
to the full limit of the law.

234
00:16:16,058 --> 00:16:19,301
And so you feel that since
every officer involved to date

235
00:16:19,312 --> 00:16:20,723
has gone free,

236
00:16:20,730 --> 00:16:23,222
Nixon failed his pledge.

237
00:16:23,232 --> 00:16:26,645
Like any other mealy-mouth
sell-out politician,

238
00:16:26,652 --> 00:16:28,768
when he found out that he could
get more votes

239
00:16:28,779 --> 00:16:32,488
by supporting Calley,
he did a complete flip flop.

240
00:16:32,492 --> 00:16:34,654
And when I saw
that the American people

241
00:16:34,660 --> 00:16:35,991
supported him in this,

242
00:16:35,995 --> 00:16:39,704
I knew then that the American
conscience was dead

243
00:16:39,707 --> 00:16:42,244
and that the great spirit
of this nation,

244
00:16:42,251 --> 00:16:45,334
which to me began back in
Boston and Virginia

245
00:16:45,338 --> 00:16:47,705
duflng
the American Revolution,

246
00:16:47,715 --> 00:16:50,002
that it could never again
be revived.

247
00:16:52,762 --> 00:16:54,844
Ladies and gentlemen
of the jury,

248
00:16:54,847 --> 00:16:56,758
have you reached a decision?

249
00:16:56,766 --> 00:16:58,677
We have, Your Honor.

250
00:16:58,684 --> 00:16:59,890
We the it"!!!

251
00:16:59,894 --> 00:17:01,430
Unanimously find Billy Jack

252
00:17:01,437 --> 00:17:04,179
guilty of involuntary
manslaughter.

253
00:17:21,040 --> 00:17:23,202
Well, that's that.

254
00:17:24,877 --> 00:17:27,039
I think you'll find
that the end

255
00:17:27,046 --> 00:17:30,459
of your little school
out there, Doc.

256
00:17:30,466 --> 00:17:32,048
Well, it's not my school,

257
00:17:32,051 --> 00:17:34,588
but, I'll take a bet on it.

258
00:17:34,595 --> 00:17:38,805
Billy Jack wasn't the center
of power of that school.

259
00:17:38,808 --> 00:17:40,970
Who, then?
